</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,425,558]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,497,522]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[351,518,497,522]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Shape and size</emphasis>
—Test small to medium-sized, ovoid, 20.4 and 
<quantity box="[1049,1149,497,521]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.18" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="21.8">21.8 mm</quantity>
TL, TW 76 and 77% TL, height 47% TL.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1268,1992,2014]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617478/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" startId="15.[151,250,1992,2014]" targetBox="[151,1436,610,1971]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1268,1992,2014]" box="[151,1268,1992,2014]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,1992,2014]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">FIGURE 10.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Loriol" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[293,548,1992,2014]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinoneidae" genus="Koehleraster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinoneoida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="abnormalis">
<emphasis box="[293,548,1992,2014]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Koehleraster abnormalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(WUSL/EI/8): A, aboral view; B, oral view; C, lateral view, right side.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617480/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" startId="16.[151,250,1756,1778]" targetBox="[151,1436,193,1735]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1435,1756,1809]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,1756,1778]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">FIGURE 11.</emphasis>
SEM images showing details on test surface of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Loriol" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[801,1058,1756,1778]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinoneidae" genus="Koehleraster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinoneoida" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="abnormalis">
<emphasis box="[801,1058,1756,1778]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Koehleraster abnormalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(WUSL/EI/8): A, apical system; B, periproct; C, orientation of pores on aboral surface; D, orientation of pores on oral surface.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1848,2017]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,353,1848,1873]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Apical system</emphasis>
—Tetrabasal; four gonopores, situated slightly anterior of centre of aboral surface, approximately 45% TL from anterior margin of test.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1848,2017]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,323,1920,1945]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Ambulacra</emphasis>
—Non-petaloid; interporiferous zone not elevated; pore-zone depressed and narrow; pores on oral surface smaller and closer together than those on aboral surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1848,2017]" box="[199,1436,1992,2017]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,355,1992,2017]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Tuberculation</emphasis>
—Test surface densely covered by small, perforate, non-crenulate primary tubercles; ring of
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,213]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">imperforate and non-crenulate miliary tubercles more or less evenly distributed among primary tubercles; primary tubercles on aboral surface smaller than those on oral surface.</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,984,1949,1971]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617482/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" startId="17.[151,250,1949,1971]" targetBox="[182,1426,291,1899]" targetPageId="17">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,984,1949,1971]" box="[151,984,1949,1971]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,1949,1971]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">FIGURE 12.</emphasis>
Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Loriol" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[500,753,1949,1971]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinoneidae" genus="Koehleraster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinoneoida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="abnormalis">
<emphasis box="[500,753,1949,1971]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Koehleraster abnormalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded in this study.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[199,313,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Peristome</emphasis>
—Smaller than periproct, length approximately 15% and 16% TL; width 17% and 21% TL; irregularly oval to triangular in shape, pointed towards interambulacrum 2 and 4, moderately sunken, situated slightly anterior to centre of oral surface, c. 47% TL from anterior margin of test to anterior edge of peristome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[199,305,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Periproct</emphasis>
—Larger than peristome, length 25% and 29% TL; width 15% and 17% TL; teardrop-shaped, slightly pointed toward peristome, longitudinally elongate; located orally in interambulacrum 5, close to peristome, 13% TL from posterior margin of test to posterior edge of periproct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,425,367,392]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Geographic range.</emphasis>
Indo-West Pacific, from 
<collectingCountry box="[721,830,367,392]" name="Mauritius" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
(de 
<bibRefCitation author="De Loriol, P." box="[886,1025,367,392]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref34555" refString="De Loriol, P. (1883) Catalogue raisonne des Echinodermes recueillis par MV de Robillard a l'ile Maurice. Memoires de la Societe de physique et d'histoire naturelle de Geneve, 28, 1 - 64." type="journal article" year="1883">Loriol 1883</bibRefCitation>
), East Indies (
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[1194,1396,368,392]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref35354" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 a) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 1. Holectypoida, Cassiduloida. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 371 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948a</bibRefCitation>
) to Coral Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Miskelly, A." box="[280,451,404,429]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref35198" refString="Miskelly, A. (2002) Sea urchins of Australia and the Indo-Pacific. Capricornica Publications, Lindfield, 179 pp." type="book" year="2002">Miskelly 2002</bibRefCitation>
), South Pacific Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[732,878,404,429]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref34415" refString="Clark, H. L. (1925 a) A Catalogue of the Recent Sea-Urchins (Echinoidea) in the Collection of the British Museum (Natural History). Oxford University Press, London, 250 pp." type="book" year="1925">Clark 1925a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[892,1091,404,428]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref35354" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 a) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 1. Holectypoida, Cassiduloida. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 371 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948a</bibRefCitation>
) and Hawaiian Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="81 - 283" refId="ref34331" refString="Clark, H. L. (1917) Hawaiian and other Pacific Echini, Echinoneidae, Nucleolitidae, Urechinidae, Echinocorythidae, Calymnidae, Pourtalesiidae, Palaestomatidae, Aeropsidae, Palaeopneustidae, Hemiasteridae, and Spatangidae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, 46, 81 - 283." type="journal article" year="1917">Clark 1917</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,824]" box="[199,842,476,501]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,430,476,501]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Bathymetric range.</emphasis>
Littoral to 
<quantity box="[557,614,476,501]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="85.0">85 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[629,830,476,500]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref35354" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 a) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 1. Holectypoida, Cassiduloida. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 371 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,629,511,536]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Observed occurrence in 
<collectingCountry box="[498,624,511,536]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
.
</emphasis>
Dead specimens were found among biogenic sands at Hiriketiya Bay Beach on the southern coast of Sri Lanka and in a coarse sand patch in a sea grass bed at 
<quantity box="[1136,1178,548,572]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="9.0">9 m</quantity>
in Baththalangunduwa on the north-western coast of Sri Lanka (
<figureCitation box="[630,716,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1949,1971]" captionTargetBox="[182,1426,291,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,265,1928]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distribution map of Koehleraster abnormalis recorded in this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617482/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). This species was first recorded from Sri Lanka by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fernando, M." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="259 - 273" refId="ref34713" refString="Fernando, M. (2006) Coral associated invertebrates: An overview of the current taxonomic status. In: Bambaradeniya, C. N. B. (Ed.), The Fauna of Sri Lanka, Section 3: Status of Marine Fauna in Sri Lanka. IUCN-The World Conservation Union, Gland, pp. 259 - 273." type="book chapter" year="2006">Fernando (2006)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,151,824]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,655,680]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
Collected materials indicate that two genera of echinoneids occur in Sri Lankan waters. At Hiriketiya Bay Beach, dead specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leske" authorityYear="1778" box="[626,795,692,717]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinoneidae" genus="Echinoneus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinoneoida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cyclostomus">
<emphasis box="[626,795,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">E. cyclostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Loriol" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[851,1011,692,717]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinoneidae" genus="Koehleraster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinoneoida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="abnormalis">
<emphasis box="[851,1011,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">K. abnormalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur together. As no live specimens of both species were collected together in their original habitat, it is inconclusive whether these two species cooccur in the same habitat. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[470,737,764,788]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref35354" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 a) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 1. Holectypoida, Cassiduloida. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 371 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen (1948a: 81)</bibRefCitation>
suggests that the two species do not co-occur at the same localities.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
